      {
        "id": "c442f9c05ae1a59dbbd8a048e6d18e8234ba4aff",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 6639,
          "name": "Toine Siebelink",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "toine.siebelink@est.tech",
          "username": "ToineSiebelink"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2023-04-25 10:31:07.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1\n\n(1 comment)\n\nlooks good, small udpat to the test need.\nand DO include a doc update! Under limitation you do have to say something now about the precedence of and or operators.\nPostures does explain it in detail here: https://www.postgresql.org/docs/7.0/operators.htm\nBut I am not suer what is the best approach we\ncoudl\na) simply say the precedence is determined by teh DB engine (currently Postgress)\nOR\nb) condense the postgress page to a singel sentence explaining the precedence for and/or)\n(Maybe Daniel can give feedback and help with B if that is what we want to do)\n(Note. you can do doc update in a separate commit)",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "85832067df74e45cf3927f1b0850567aaefd5173",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 6742,
          "name": "Daniel Hanrahan",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "daniel.hanrahan@est.tech",
          "username": "danielhanrahan"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2023-04-25 12:40:15.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1\n\n> Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1\n> \n> (1 comment)\n> \n> looks good, small udpat to the test need.\n> and DO include a doc update! Under limitation you do have to say something now about the precedence of and or operators.\n> Postures does explain it in detail here: https://www.postgresql.org/docs/7.0/operators.htm\n> But I am not suer what is the best approach we\n> coudl\n> a) simply say the precedence is determined by teh DB engine (currently Postgress)\n> OR\n> b) condense the postgress page to a singel sentence explaining the precedence for and/or)\n> (Maybe Daniel can give feedback and help with B if that is what we want to do)\n> (Note. you can do doc update in a separate commit)\n\nYes, basically AND has precedence over OR, so ANDs get evaluated first.\n\nFor example, given this query:\n //addresses[@house-number=2 or @street=\"Grafton Street\" and @town=\"Maynooth\" or @county=\"Dublin\"]\n\nThis is equivalent to:\n //addresses[@house-number=2 or (@street=\"Grafton Street\" and @town=\"Maynooth\") or @county=\"Dublin\"]\n\nSome general examples of SQL AND/OR precedence:\n A and B or C and D => (A and B) or (C and D)\n A and B or C or  D => (A and B) or C or D\n A or  B or C and D => A or B or (C and D)\n A or B and C and D => A or (B and C and D)\n A or B and C or  D => A or (B and C) or D\n\nSo ANDs get evaluated before ORs.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
